<Layout title="Section 1 – Health Assessment">
  <h1>Section 1: Health Assessment</h1>
  <p><em>Competency 7093.4.1 – Performs Health Assessments</em></p>
  <p>
    You will obtain a health history, perform a general head-to-toe physical assessment on
    adult patients, complete a focused older adult assessment, obtain vital signs, and
    determine pain level.
  </p>

  <h2>Page 1: Health History &amp; General Physical</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Learning Objective:</strong> Obtain a health history and perform a general
    head-to-toe physical assessment while maintaining person-centered safety precautions.
  </p>

  <h3>Health History Components</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Chief complaint and history of present illness</li>
    <li>Past medical/surgical history, allergies, current medications</li>
    <li>Family history, social history, review of systems</li>
    <li>Subjective data (what the patient reports) vs. objective data (what the nurse observes)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Head-to-Toe Physical Assessment</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>General Survey:</strong> Level of consciousness, appearance, affect, hygiene, distress.</li>
    <li><strong>Neurological:</strong> Orientation (person, place, time, event); Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS); PERRLA.</li>
    <li><strong>Cardiovascular:</strong> Heart rate/rhythm; peripheral pulses; capillary refill; edema grading.</li>
    <li><strong>Respiratory:</strong> Rate, depth, effort; breath sounds (vesicular, crackles, wheezes, rhonchi, stridor).</li>
    <li><strong>Gastrointestinal:</strong> Bowel sounds × 4 quadrants; tenderness; last bowel movement.</li>
    <li><strong>Genitourinary:</strong> Urine output (min 0.5 mL/kg/hr); color, clarity, odor.</li>
    <li><strong>Musculoskeletal:</strong> Muscle strength grading (0–5); ROM; gait, balance.</li>
    <li><strong>Integumentary:</strong> Color, temperature, moisture, turgor; pressure injury staging.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Essential Lessons (Sherpath, Section 1 – Chapter 16)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Adult Head-to-Toe Examination</li>
    <li>Focused Assessments</li>
    <li>Recognize Cues from Assessment Data</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Page 2: Older Adult Assessment</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Learning Objective:</strong> Obtain a focused assessment of an older adult.
  </p>
  <p>
    Older adult assessments must consider age-related physiological changes and cognitive
    function. Use frameworks specific to gerontological nursing to identify atypical
    presentations of illness.
  </p>

  <h3>Key Gerontological Assessment Areas</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Physical cues:</strong> Skin turgor, mobility limitations, sensory deficits, polypharmacy.</li>
    <li><strong>Cognitive cues:</strong> Orientation, memory, executive function; screen for delirium vs. dementia.</li>
    <li><strong>Mood &amp; functional ability:</strong> Depression screening (GDS), ADL/IADL independence.</li>
    <li><strong>Fall risk:</strong> Orthostatic hypotension, gait changes, environmental hazards.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="tip">
    <strong>💡 Key Point</strong>
    Older adults often present with atypical symptoms. Confusion, falling, or decreased
    appetite may be the first sign of infection or illness rather than classic symptoms.
  </div>

  <h3>Essential Lessons (Sherpath, Section 1 – Chapter 8)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Best Practices for Clinical Cues, Documentation, and Evaluation</li>
    <li>Physical and Cognitive Cues</li>
    <li>Mood, Functional Ability, and Comprehensive Cues</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Page 3: Vital Signs &amp; Pain Assessment</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Learning Objective:</strong> Demonstrate vital signs and pain assessment on an
    adult patient.
  </p>

  <h3>Vital Signs Normal Ranges (Adult)</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Vital Sign</th><th>Normal Range</th><th>Key Notes</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Temperature (oral)</td><td>36.5 – 37.5 °C (97.7 – 99.5 °F)</td><td>Fever &gt; 38 °C; hypothermia &lt; 35 °C</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Heart Rate</td><td>60 – 100 bpm</td><td>Tachycardia &gt; 100; bradycardia &lt; 60</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Respirations</td><td>12 – 20 breaths/min</td><td>Count unobtrusively for full accuracy</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Blood Pressure</td><td>&lt; 120/80 mmHg (normal)</td><td>Hypertensive crisis &gt; 180/120</td></tr>
      <tr><td>SpO₂</td><td>95 – 100%</td><td>&lt; 90% requires urgent intervention</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Pain Assessment Scales</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Scale</th><th>Best Used For</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>NRS (0–10)</td><td>Adults who can self-report</td><td>0 = no pain; 10 = worst imaginable</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Wong-Baker FACES</td><td>Children ≥ 3 yr; literacy challenges</td><td>Six faces from happy to crying</td></tr>
      <tr><td>FLACC</td><td>Infants; non-verbal patients</td><td>Face, Legs, Activity, Cry, Consolability (0–10)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>CPOT</td><td>Critically ill/sedated</td><td>Critical-Care Pain Observation Tool (0–8)</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="tip">
    <strong>💡 OLDCARTS Mnemonic</strong>
    Onset, Location, Duration, Characteristics, Aggravating factors, Relieving factors,
    Treatment, Severity — use to fully characterize any pain complaint.
  </div>

  <h3>Clinical Skills</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Assessment: Orthostatic Vital Signs</li>
    <li>Taking Temperatures</li>
    <li>Assessing Radial Pulse, Apical Pulse, Apical-Radial Pulse</li>
    <li>Assessing Respiration: Rate, Rhythm, and Effort</li>
    <li>Obtaining Blood Pressure (One-Step and Two-Step Methods)</li>
    <li>Measuring Oxygen Saturation with Pulse Oximetry</li>
    <li>Assessing Pain</li>
    <li>Measuring Height and Weight</li>
    <li>Head-to-Toe Assessment</li>
    <li>Shadow Health Digital Clinical Experience</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Key Terms</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Subjective data:</strong> Patient-reported symptoms, feelings, history.</li>
    <li><strong>Objective data:</strong> Nurse-observed, measured, or detected findings.</li>
    <li><strong>PERRLA:</strong> Pupils Equal, Round, Reactive to Light and Accommodation.</li>
    <li><strong>GCS:</strong> Glasgow Coma Scale (3–15); assesses eye, verbal, and motor responses.</li>
    <li><strong>Orthostatic hypotension:</strong> Drop in systolic BP ≥ 20 mmHg or diastolic ≥ 10 mmHg when moving from lying to standing.</li>
    <li><strong>OLDCARTS:</strong> Mnemonic for comprehensive pain characterization.</li>
  </ul>
</Layout>
